Merge pull request #971 from satta/ltrdigest-hmmscan-threaded

use concurrent communication with hmmscan

use concurrent communication with hmmscan

We noticed that the current implementation of passing data to and
receiving data from HMMER's hmmscan in the GtLTRdigestPdomVisitor relies
on the pipe buffer to store input and output while a single thread is
handling writing and reading sequentially. This obviously causes
problems once the buffer size is exceeded, with one side of the
communication waiting for the other to read the flushed buffer contents.
This resulted in #970 and probably also #962.
This commit uses separate threads for the read and write sides of the
communication.

Merge pull request #944 from satta/gcc-10

Enable building on GCC 10

declare hashmap type as extern

This fixes a build issue with GCC 10.
Closes #941.

make sure to not ignore snprintf output

GCC 10 will warn about the (here intended) silent string truncation
done by snprintf() unless the return value is handled.
Obviously this will break the build as we use -Werror. We
circumvent the problem by checking the output value and printing a
warning if we notice a truncation.

Remove assertion. Bugfix.

The case that this assertion tests can actually happen. It is not an error
when condenseq->ldb_nelems equals 0. It just means that the compression
is bad because no redundancies were found so that the number of links
is zero. To see an example when this happens, execute
gt condenseq compress sequence
and let sequence be the encoded sequence of the sequence found under
http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/NC_000913.3
After removal of the assertion everything is fine. Otherwise we get
an assertion failure.

Merge pull request #408 from yeban/zsh_completion

Add scripts to generate zsh completion function for gt.

I will have to test this :) and then we can think about the additions you mentioned.

Add scripts to generate zsh completion function for gt.

Parse output of `-help` for each tool (gt <tool> -help) and combine them into a
zsh completion function.

Usage:
    $ <path to genometools repo>/script/gen_zsh_completion > _gt
    $ mv _gt <some dir containing other zsh completion functions>
    $ exec $SHELL
    $ gt <TAB>

Limitations:
* assumes `gt` to be in PATH.
* list of tools is hardcoded in the script. Probably should parse the list of
  tools from `gt -help` instead.
* doesn't know to deal with `-help+` option of some tools.
* only first line of help text for an option is used (`gt -seed` for example).

Notes:
* help2comp.py was borrowed from [1] with a minor modification. The change is
  marked in the script.
* [1] is GPL2 licensed. Not sure if that's incompatible with gt's license.
* Template for completion function borrowed from [2].

[1]: https://github.com/RobSis/zsh-completion-generator
[2]: http://wikimatze.de/writing-zsh-completion-for-padrino/

Signed-off-by: Anurag Priyam <anurag08priyam@gmail.com>

Merge pull request #194 from satta/ruby_stuff

Ruby optimizations and bugfixes

gtruby: be more economical with scarce callback functions

The Ruby::DL engine only allows for 10 globally allocated callback
functions. This makes it impractical to register a callback for each
possible node type handler in a custom visitor if it is not implemented.
This commit only registers callbacks for node types for which handlers
are present in the GT::CustomVisitor subclass. This can give you 1-2
additional possible custom visitors before the limit kicks in.

adjust GFF3 escaping code

This commit introduces the following new behavior:

- Spaces are now allowed and need not be escaped, according to the spec.
- Any valid escape sequence can now be unescaped.
- Mandatory escaped characters are always escaped (control characters, [;=%&,\t]).
- Non-hex sequences (e.g. '%ZS') are ignored and NOT unescaped.

a pointer to it in a queue, to be retrieved when using the
GtSequenceBuffer. Afterwards the memory for the descriptions is almost
always freed, making this a malloc/copy/free overhead linear with the number
of sequences. This commit introduces a buffer which reuses memory for
descriptions using parsing, and requires only one small copy operation
whenever the sequence output buffer is empty, instead of at every
sequence.
This comes with a slight interface change as, obviously, ownership
of description string memory now has to remain with the buffer object.

streamify LTRharvest

much better with the rest of the GenomeTools. The main prediction
engine is realized as a stream source of LTR retrotransposon
annotations which are then passed through a number of additional
streams to create GFF3, tabular and FASTA output.

actually handle Lua callback runtime errors

This completes a quick hack introduced earlier which allowed Lua callback
functions to produce node-specific style values. However, error messages
from the callbacks were quietly discarded, making it difficult to debug
custom functions.
This commit fixes this by properly checking the results of protected
calls to Lua for errors and forwarding the messages to the drawing
engine.

This commit removes some functionality from the Style file due to
design issues that are rather solved by reimplementation.
In particular, the type-specific options 'max_num_lines' and
'split_lines' have been removed and are only usable via their
global counterpart in the 'format' section.
This is due to the fact that they do not actually reference types,
but rather tracks, whose caption strings may not be identical to
types.

introduce FeatureTypeFactory, make GenomeFeatureType an object

This is the first step to introduce different genome feature type checkers.
With this implementation every GenomeFeature has a single GenomeFeatureType
object (with internally keeps track of its ``father'', the FeatureTypeFactory).
Since the FeatureTypeFactory has to be used to create new GenomeFeatureTypes
they can be used multiple times (to save space).
The downside is that the FeatureTypeFactory owns all GenomeFeatureType and
therefore it has to stay in memory until all GenomeFeatures have been removed.

Some changes to the Makefile:
- All GT_* variables now designate flags, libraries etc. that are
  specific to the internal build process of genometools.
- The common makefile variables like CFLAGS are used for settings
  that must also be employed by anyone linking against any of the
  libgt* libraries.
- Said variables will also be exported via a script installed in the
  bin subdirectory of the installation prefix. Thus the user can
  retrieve the required settings for compilation like this:
  CC=`genometools-config -cc`
  CFLAGS=`genometools-config -cflags`
  CPPFLAGS=`genometools-config -cppflags`
  LDFLAGS=`genometools-config -ldflags`

- To build a tool that requires the C++ part of the library use
  corresponding cxx options.

- See 'genometools-config -usage' for possible options.

put an end to the Doxygen experiment

Reasons:
- the documentation clutters the source files and usually doesn't add any
  additional information (see the history of src/libgtview/ for an example)
- the documentation is out of sync very often (see also the src/libgtview/
  history), which further degrades its usefulness
- the information is much too low-level (low-level information is already
  sufficiently documented in the source code itself)
- libgtcore and libgtext will never be documented in such a way (it simply looks
  too ugly)

Further directions:
- write high-level documentation (in tutorial style, giving examples on how to
  use the libraries), probably shown as HTML (hyperlinks are an absolute must
  here). design.html is already a step in this direction.
- It is probably best to extract this information directly from the source
  files (to reduce the out-of-sync problem).
